reviewText: This 1991 dvd, filmed as JT and his band were preparing for the tour for his then new album "New Moon Shine," is a unique live dvd like no other: recorded at his barn in Squibnocket on Martha's Vineyard, "Squibnocket" captures Taylor at his loosest and a most relaxed; the beautiful, breezy atmosphere lends greatly to the quality of the performance, as JT and the band cut loose on 15 classic songs played and sung expertly, including "Fire and Rain, "You've Got a Friend, "Sweet Baby James," and many more. Interspersed is a fun and revealing interview with the artist discussing the songs, his involvement in the writing process, and many other entertaining tidbits that will fascinate fans. The sound and picture are glorious. The performance is unforgettable. "Squibnocket" is an essential purchase.
summary: A Warm and Wonderful Performance With Incomparable Atmosphere

reviewText: This DVD was nice, except it could have been longer.  Home location, barn setting was nice, serene images and laid back style. JT is great at this type of thing and the fans should love this.  I was hoping for more side interviews from him... personal stuff, maybe him commenting on his home scenery and personal tidbits on his songs... still very nice.

reviewText: I have been a big james Taylor fan for years. This man can sing better than almost anyone I have seen. I would like to say something about the people no longer with us. First Brother Don Grolnick. Carlos Vegas were both very important in James's music at the time. Valerie Carter and the backgrand singers are very good. James is really my most favorite singer in the last 40 years. I don't know when sweet baby james came out but I was A fan. I would like to say that James was my favorite of all the singer songwriters. I miss carly and him singing together.

reviewText: A terrific collection with reminiscences that take you into Taylor's life.  An enjoyable hour with 15 of his finer efforts.  The staging, song selection, and audio quality make for a fine evening.

reviewText: I first saw this concert on the Disney Channel in the early eighties and taped it on VHS, but eventually the tape wore out.  It features many of Taylor's greatest hits as well as several songs from his then new album New Moon Shine, especially The Frozen Man, which is my personal favorite James Taylor song.  Due to the time in which it was made, the picture is not up to today's digital standards, but the music is well worth the price, and I do recommend this DVD.
